Have I mentioned it all the circumstances under which I experienced the opening here at Oregon State?

26
00:01:40,000 --> 00:01:42,000
Oh, no, no.

27
00:01:42,000 --> 00:01:51,000
Oh, well, I had been working at Caltech for many years after my doctorate.

28
00:01:51,000 --> 00:01:55,000
And, well, many, five or six.

29
00:01:55,000 --> 00:02:03,000
And I was actively engaged in research and I was stopped in the hole one day by Carl Neiman,

30
00:02:03,000 --> 00:02:08,000
who was a distinguished organic chemist and whom I knew quite well.

31
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:15,000
He said, can I receive the letter from a former colleague of mine?

32
00:02:15,000 --> 00:02:21,000
A man I went to graduate school with with Wisconsin, who was now at Oregon State.

33
00:02:21,000 --> 00:02:23,000
And he said, they have an opening there.

34
00:02:23,000 --> 00:02:27,000
And he wondered whether I had anybody who would be interested or we here at Caltech,

35
00:02:27,000 --> 00:02:30,000
if anybody who might be interested.

36
00:02:30,000 --> 00:02:38,000
I just thought I'd mention it to you in passing because I remember you were in Oregon State undergrad.

37
00:02:38,000 --> 00:02:51,000
So, at this time, my wife was pretty unhappy in California and Macedonia because of the air pollution.

38
00:02:51,000 --> 00:03:03,000
Our first son was about to be born and she wanted to raise him in that environment.

39
00:03:03,000 --> 00:03:07,000
I said, yes, I'd better explore this.

40
00:03:07,000 --> 00:03:17,000
And so I wrote them to E.C. Gilbert, who wrote back, indeed, they did have an opening.

41
00:03:17,000 --> 00:03:28,000
And one thing followed another and it turned out that my wife and I were going to drive North to Oregon to visit my parents,

42
00:03:28,000 --> 00:03:32,000
who lived at that time in Astoria.

43
00:03:32,000 --> 00:03:41,000
And I said to Gilbert that I would stop on route and talk with him and members of the faculty and discuss the opening.

44
00:03:41,000 --> 00:03:47,000
Then I got another letter from a guy named Bill Colville, William E. Colville,

45
00:03:47,000 --> 00:03:57,000
who let me know in no uncertain terms that the reason this was a job was because he had managed to get the president of the University of A.L. Strand

46
00:03:57,000 --> 00:04:03,000
to commit to two new faculty hires in chemistry.

47
00:04:03,000 --> 00:04:15,000
And it turns out that at that time, well, let me put it this way, Earl Gilbert and Bill Colville were not on the best of terms.

48
00:04:15,000 --> 00:04:27,000
Gilbert was a department chairman and Colville was a professor who did almost, did no research on sight,

49
00:04:27,000 --> 00:04:30,000
but had some mining claims and other things.

50
00:04:30,000 --> 00:04:44,000
And it was kind of an open, free-handed, back-slopping type, a member of the country club and a new E.L. Strand fairly well.

51
00:04:44,000 --> 00:05:04,000
And he complained that the freshman at Oregon State and incoming students were not being given proper instruction because there weren't enough professional staff involved in this, just graduate teaching assistants and so on.

52
00:05:05,000 --> 00:05:16,000
And he managed to convince Strand that perhaps there should be some positions set up.

53
00:05:16,000 --> 00:05:25,000
And these would people, of course, would be nominally responsible to Colville since he was running the whole program.

54
00:05:25,000 --> 00:05:36,000
And the main purpose of the main task of these people were going to be that they would sort of ride herd on all the teaching assistants.

55
00:05:36,000 --> 00:05:41,000
So they would patrol the laboratories, make sure that the teaching assistants were doing their job.

56
00:05:41,000 --> 00:05:46,000
They would, of course, have some responsibilities themselves, bought in the freshman program.

57
00:05:46,000 --> 00:06:02,000
They would hold recitations and they would be in this way and be responsible for laboratories and then, as I mentioned, patrol the laboratories regularly.

58
00:06:03,000 --> 00:06:16,000
So I immediately sensed that there was something, there was a bit of an adversarial relationship between Gilbert and Colville.

59
00:06:16,000 --> 00:06:26,000
And Gilbert, of course, was interested in hiring somebody who could also increase the research potential of the faculty.

60
00:06:27,000 --> 00:06:31,000
Colville wasn't in the least interested in whether these guys could do any research or not.

61
00:06:31,000 --> 00:06:37,000
He just wanted them as sort of major domos.

62
00:06:37,000 --> 00:06:50,000
And so I learned all of this in more detail when I came and talked with Gilbert and talked with Colville.

63
00:06:51,000 --> 00:07:14,000
And I also had numerous conversations with other members of the faculty, people who have passed on now, Tom Nauros, Wendell Slavell, everybody that was on the faculty that I had known before.

64
00:07:15,000 --> 00:07:24,000
And after concluding all these interviews, we drove on down to my terrace, came back to California.

65
00:07:24,000 --> 00:07:37,000
I had told Gilbert it was still a guy who was officially in charge of the hiring that I would think it over and I'd let him know.

66
00:07:38,000 --> 00:08:03,000
So after I got back to Pasadena, I felt for a long time about this, and decided that the conditions of this job were such that I found it unlikely to be able to get my research program going at Oregon State in a reasonable length of time, so I declined the offer, which was $5,500 for nine months.

67
00:08:03,000 --> 00:08:10,000
No, no, nine months, but spread over 10 months.

68
00:08:10,000 --> 00:08:20,000
Well, my wife was very unhappy about this because she liked Oregon more like Oslo, where she grew up in Norway.

69
00:08:20,000 --> 00:08:32,000
As she put it, there was so water in the rivers of Pinarigan and trees in the forest where she couldn't see that in LA.

70
00:08:32,000 --> 00:08:44,000
We drove across a bridge, one place, and I pointed out that this was the San Gabriel River. She looked down, there was no water, it was just a dry wash.

71
00:08:44,000 --> 00:08:53,000
And we went through the San Gabriel forest on the outskirts, so that there's nothing but sagebrush, that's the source of her comments.

72
00:08:53,000 --> 00:09:02,000
At any rate, she was very unhappy about this. And a few days later, I got a call from Gilbert saying he was very sorry to receive my letter.

73
00:09:02,000 --> 00:09:20,000
He had very much hoped that I would accept the job. And he said he wondered if they were able to increase the starting, so I'll read a little bit what I reconsider.

74
00:09:20,000 --> 00:09:32,000
And I said at this time, the home life was a little frosty because at least it was so disappointed. So I said, okay, I'll do that.

75
00:09:32,000 --> 00:09:36,000
Have I told you any of this at all? No, okay.

76
00:09:36,000 --> 00:09:47,000
So the offer came back and he said we can pay you two or three hundred dollars more per year. That's maybe five percent or six percent increase.

77
00:09:47,000 --> 00:10:03,000
And so I asked Paul what he thought about all this. And he invited me to come up to his home one evening after hours, five o'clock or so.

78
00:10:03,000 --> 00:10:15,000
I can't remember exactly, so I went up to 4,500 per point, whatever the street number is, or yeah, he's Allison, he's out on the Miranda and discussed the job.

79
00:10:15,000 --> 00:10:32,000
I've been very active in research at Caltech, and had a number of published papers, lots of things going, and I expressed to him my fear that I was not going to be able to get my research program going at Oregon State because it involved the construction of apparatus.

80
00:10:32,000 --> 00:10:44,000
You saw that apparatus. I had to build that by hand. There were extremely limited machine shop facilities, nothing in the chemistry department at all.

81
00:10:44,000 --> 00:11:00,000
And I didn't see how I could get that instrument built at Oregon State. So I expressed all this to him and then told him that the actual number of hours that I was expected to be in contact with students

82
00:11:00,000 --> 00:11:20,000
was something like 15 or 16 hours a week, just in the hands-on contact. That's about 30 percent, or a little bit more than that, 35 percent of the total time, not counting preparation or anything.

83
00:11:20,000 --> 00:11:28,000
Anne Pauling, sort of lean back in his chair, we were sitting side by side looking out over the valley and the swimming pool.

84
00:11:28,000 --> 00:11:36,000
He said, well, he said, I don't know. He says 15 hours. He said, when I was at Oregon State, I was teaching 40 hours a week.

85
00:11:36,000 --> 00:11:48,000
That was the year that he was a sophomore and had been asked to handle a course for young women in home economics.

86
00:11:48,000 --> 00:11:56,000
I think at those who were taking chemistry as a requirement, that's where he met his wife A. The Helen. But anyway, that's the story, you know.

87
00:11:56,000 --> 00:12:14,000
So anyhow, he said 40 hours. He said, I don't know. He said, I think that Oregon State will not be a first-class institution for research in my time. And probably not on yours. These are his words.

88
00:12:14,000 --> 00:12:27,000
He said, on the other hand, that's not really important in a bigger sense. He said, if you didn't get your program going, these will be very happy there. Oregon is a wonderful place to live, as you and I know.

89
00:12:27,000 --> 00:12:35,000
He said, I don't know. I think it might be worthwhile giving a chance. I think you could make it go on. You'd be very happy there.

90
00:12:35,000 --> 00:12:55,000
So with that encouragement, I told Gilbert up and said, yes, I would accept the offer. And my wife, of course, was delighted at this because at this time our son had just been born.

91
00:12:55,000 --> 00:13:15,000
And we lived in Pasadena, down below, not far from Caltech. And the smog would roll in the morning, about 11 o'clock. And she'd take the baby in, close all the doors and windows.

92
00:13:16,000 --> 00:13:26,000
Keep them closed till about four in the afternoon when the winds reverse their direction and swept all the smog back out to sea again. And she could open things up.

93
00:13:26,000 --> 00:13:40,000
It was pretty hot, too. So I had a hose in this garden cottage that I put on the root and turned on the water to keep it cool during the time that she was so to speak incarcerated.

94
00:13:40,000 --> 00:13:53,000
Anyway, that fall, I told Gilbert that I wouldn't be able to come in the fall by the fall term, but I could come January 1st.

95
00:13:53,000 --> 00:14:01,000
This was January 1st, was 1956. So this was all in 1955. This conversation went on.

96
00:14:01,000 --> 00:14:20,000
So I had come January, we drove north after Christmas in times of a huge storm that actually led to flooding. This was a fine way for my wife to be introduced to the worst vertical of Alice.

97
00:14:20,000 --> 00:14:35,000
You don't know anything today about how it was then, but we drove up to Eugene, got the junction city, and it turned out that the 99 West was closed because of water and the roads.

98
00:14:35,000 --> 00:14:46,000
But there was a bus going up 99 East to Albany and I, with our car, the baby in the back, and we followed this bus very carefully up sometimes.

99
00:14:46,000 --> 00:14:56,000
The water almost up to the hubcaps of the car got to Albany. And then it turned out that the road from Albany to Corvallas was okay.

100
00:14:56,000 --> 00:15:12,000
It wasn't underwater yet, but the road from Corvallas South on 99 West was underwater. So by that we managed to get to Corvallas, and by three arrangements we had run out of the house of a faculty member that was going to be away for three months.

101
00:15:12,000 --> 00:15:29,000
So we had a place to move into immediately, all furnished, very nice house on Chintimini, over there against the hill and south. Well, you know where it is.

102
00:15:29,000 --> 00:15:48,000
It was very nice. And it turned out that everything was flooded the following day or two in Corvallas. You could hardly get around at all. And then it turned cold later on, snow came and so on.

103
00:15:48,000 --> 00:16:02,000
So that was my introduction to Corvallas. I showed up to work on one of the early days and Gilbert told me, oh, they had a kind of a bonus to give me.

104
00:16:02,000 --> 00:16:20,000
And that was that I was going to be assigned to teach a graduate course and physical chemistry to organically and others.

105
00:16:20,000 --> 00:16:40,000
Well, this sounded like a bonus to him, but for somebody just coming there, I mean this was a lecture thrill or as a week and I had never done this course before. So I had all those lectures to prepare as well as stuff I was expected to do under Bill Coldwell's regime.

106
00:16:40,000 --> 00:17:03,000
So I had a very, very busy time and with a newborn in the house of my wife, you know, trying hard to the customer's self to life in a new place with a new baby in a husband who was up to his ears and work wasn't very easy.

107
00:17:03,000 --> 00:17:23,000
I was pretty discouraged at the end of that term. And as the term drew on, I took care to write down on a piece of paper divided into days and hours of the day for a week each week.

108
00:17:23,000 --> 00:17:40,000
How much time I was actually spending in duties connected with teaching by connected with that man in the in with students one on one preparation, including evening hours and everything else.

109
00:17:41,000 --> 00:17:58,000
And I was averaging that first term, 56 hours a week, only in teaching related duties. And so my fear is about getting my program started on the research side. Well, well born out by that first experience.

110
00:17:58,000 --> 00:18:15,000
And of course, I was expected not only to have a program going, getting my research going, but I had to build this apparatus, which meant that I had to design it, sit down with, I think I showed you just briefly, folders with those drawings in there.

111
00:18:15,000 --> 00:18:34,000
I had a drawing table in my office. And so I spent a lot of time with drawing these things. And then Professor Youngter and Physics had a fine physics shop. And I went across to see him and he agreed, you see my life actually, to allow one of the people in physics.

112
00:18:34,000 --> 00:18:45,000
Physics, I think they had three or four machinists who would be assigned to my job. And he would do everything and he and I would be in one to one contact all the time.

113
00:18:45,000 --> 00:18:58,000
He reserved the right to retake this man off for any projects that physics needed, of course, since he was employed by physics and using the physics facilities.

114
00:18:58,000 --> 00:19:11,000
And that worked out just beautifully. Took a long time to get the apparatus built three or four years, but it was finally done and put together and we managed to make it go.

115
00:19:11,000 --> 00:19:22,000
So Ed Youngter's facilities and his kindness really are responsible for getting me off the ground at Oregon State.

116
00:19:23,000 --> 00:19:26,000
So would describe the apparatus a little bit for me.

117
00:19:26,000 --> 00:19:28,000
Sorry. Describe the apparatus for me.

118
00:19:28,000 --> 00:19:35,000
Oh, well, the apparatus is what is called an electron diffraction unit.

119
00:19:35,000 --> 00:19:51,000
It consists of a, the essential feature of it is an electron gun that will produce a well-colonated beam of electrons at the potential of about 60 kiloboles.

120
00:19:51,000 --> 00:20:01,000
It's a very energetic beam on the scale of the way chemistry operates.

121
00:20:01,000 --> 00:20:07,000
That beam is admitted into a large vacuum chamber.

122
00:20:07,000 --> 00:20:15,000
In my apparatus, the whole thing is mounted vertically, so the beam comes down into this vacuum chamber.

123
00:20:15,000 --> 00:20:26,000
And at the bottom of the beam, let's say, is a detecting beam, which is in my case, photographic film.

124
00:20:26,000 --> 00:20:31,000
In those days, there's a photographic plate, but it's no photographic film.

125
00:20:31,000 --> 00:20:44,000
And this photographic film is eight by ten inches square and is perpendicular to the beam and is moved into position by mechanism that I built into the apparatus.

126
00:20:45,000 --> 00:20:56,000
And the apparatus is designed to study the structures of molecules in the gas phase by diffracting this beam of electrons from them.

127
00:20:56,000 --> 00:21:13,000
So we have a long nozzle that protrudes into the apparatus with a tip that passes that stops just about a millimeter short of where there's very fine high-powered electron beam is coming down.

128
00:21:14,000 --> 00:21:30,000
Now, if in this nozzle, which is a two with a fine tip on it, you admit a gas into the chamber, the gas shoots out the nozzle tip, intersects the electron beam at right angles and produces what is called a diffraction pattern.

129
00:21:30,000 --> 00:21:42,000
This diffraction pattern consists of what happens is, of course, it's recorded on this photographic film at the underneath the nozzle.

130
00:21:42,000 --> 00:21:45,000
And perpendicular to the beam.

131
00:21:45,000 --> 00:21:54,000
So the diffraction pattern is recorded on this in a set of diffuse rings of varying intensity.

132
00:21:54,000 --> 00:22:10,000
And the spacing of these rings and their shapes of the pattern contain all the structural information about the length of the interatomic distances in the molecule.

133
00:22:12,000 --> 00:22:24,000
And so we take these patterns and we analyze them and out of that we can deduce the intimate details of the structures of these molecules in the gas phase.

134
00:22:24,000 --> 00:22:36,000
That is essentially, it's a structure of a single molecule because so far apart, they don't interact with one another as they shoot into the apparatus.

135
00:22:36,000 --> 00:22:45,000
And so that's what I was charged with or what I wanted to build and which I finally got going for all those years.

136
00:22:45,000 --> 00:22:48,000
It's still running and running.

137
00:22:48,000 --> 00:23:03,000
Yeah, and it is running and right now and running beautifully, we just did an experiment last week, beautiful patterns we got for a new molecule or interested in.

138
00:23:03,000 --> 00:23:18,000
It doesn't take long for the experiment as quite interesting. The technique is developed enormously since the days when I first entered the field at Caltech as a graduate student.

139
00:23:18,000 --> 00:23:38,000
And now the experiment that lasts is diffraction pattern. You expose the photographic film to the diffraction pattern for only two or three minutes and you might want to make five different films or ten different films.

140
00:23:38,000 --> 00:23:45,000
So all tools you can do the entire experiment in a day if you push it, everything.

141
00:23:45,000 --> 00:23:52,000
And that's all the data you need for what might be for a graduate student a year and a half of work analyzing it.

142
00:23:52,000 --> 00:24:02,000
So the apparatus mostly sits unused because we can quickly gather all the data we knew.

143
00:24:02,000 --> 00:24:07,000
So I've had a lot of visitors who have come, used the apparatus.

144
00:24:07,000 --> 00:24:14,000
And if I had a technician I could supply all the diffraction data for every group in the world.

145
00:24:14,000 --> 00:24:21,000
This technician did nothing but take diffraction pictures of substances involved.

146
00:24:21,000 --> 00:24:32,000
Now it may be a little more complicated because these are gas phase molecules. We admit them in the chamber as a gas.

147
00:24:32,000 --> 00:24:38,000
But that doesn't mean that they have to be a gas as you look at them. You can put them on the table.

148
00:24:38,000 --> 00:24:43,000
The factors you've got to get them into the gas phase in order to make this experiment work.

149
00:24:43,000 --> 00:24:50,000
Well, we have a set of ovens and heated nozzles so we can heat these things up and get the vapor.

150
00:24:50,000 --> 00:24:57,000
C60 that we have worked on, of course, is very intractable, has no vapor pressure at all to speak of.

151
00:24:57,000 --> 00:25:10,000
So we had to heat this substance in an oven to 800 and some odd degrees Celsius in order to get the tiniest bit of vapor from it.

152
00:25:10,000 --> 00:25:20,000
But that was sufficient to give us the diffraction pattern and we were able to determine the structure of this material which is a carbon-like powder on the table.

153
00:25:20,000 --> 00:25:32,000
So we have all sorts of auxiliary apparatus which allows us to produce gas molecules from lots of different circumstances.

154
00:25:32,000 --> 00:25:37,000
So it works very nicely. I'm very happy with it.

155
00:25:37,000 --> 00:25:55,000
I should add as a post-cryptolist that this technique was very powerful through the 40s and 50s and 60s even in the 70s.

156
00:25:56,000 --> 00:26:06,000
But there are other techniques that have developed in the meantime too and so there are fewer laboratories in the world doing this work.

157
00:26:06,000 --> 00:26:17,000
When I came to Oregon State and got mine going, there were about, there were only two laboratories in the United States.

158
00:26:17,000 --> 00:26:23,000
Did this kind of work? Mine and a laboratory at Michigan.

159
00:26:23,000 --> 00:26:30,000
There were other people who, well there was another apparatus built.

160
00:26:30,000 --> 00:26:34,000
It didn't, it worked for a while but not very long.

161
00:26:34,000 --> 00:26:38,000
And there was one of Texas that was built similar to look.

162
00:26:38,000 --> 00:26:49,000
But it was built in the physics department and the interest there was not the same as the interest that chemists had.

163
00:26:49,000 --> 00:26:54,000
And so it worked for a while and then it stopped.

164
00:26:54,000 --> 00:27:03,000
And later on there were apparatuses in Britain.

165
00:27:03,000 --> 00:27:14,000
There was one at Edinburgh. And later on, and still extant, is one in Reading, England.

166
00:27:15,000 --> 00:27:19,000
There was one in Germany, they were very active in Germany.

167
00:27:19,000 --> 00:27:31,000
And when I first started there was one in Belgium and one in Holland and several in at that time the Soviet Union.

168
00:27:31,000 --> 00:27:40,000
And two or three laboratories in Japan, all of them had apparatus and could do experiments.

169
00:27:40,000 --> 00:27:48,000
All those were gone except the apparatus in Reading.

170
00:27:48,000 --> 00:28:01,000
The apparatus in Germany by the way, the man who was the professor who was in charge of that laboratory retired.

171
00:28:01,000 --> 00:28:04,000
His name was Heinz Oberhummer.

172
00:28:04,000 --> 00:28:21,000
And his apparatus has been transferred to an inorganic chemist who is using it as kind of an exaggerate to his main work which is the preparation and interesting inorganic compounds.

173
00:28:21,000 --> 00:28:25,000
And as a part of that he wants to know what those structures are.

174
00:28:25,000 --> 00:28:36,000
The apparatus in Reading is still extant but the man who was in charge of it before has now retired.

175
00:28:36,000 --> 00:28:46,000
And a woman that was working with him has a permanent position at the university but she's heavily involved with teaching and has very little time to work with it.

