190
00:30:52,000 --> 00:31:00,000
The question then you're really asking is how do you go from that to determine how molecules put together?

191
00:31:01,000 --> 00:31:14,000
Well, it turns out that these rings are related to the structure of the molecule by some, according to theory, by in a rather simple way.

192
00:31:14,000 --> 00:31:18,000
I'll keep it as simple as I possibly can.

193
00:31:18,000 --> 00:31:34,000
Every interatomic distance in the molecule creates an effect on this film, a pattern that consists of nothing more than a sine wave going from the middle out.

194
00:31:34,000 --> 00:31:41,000
Now a sine wave just goes up and down, up and down, up and down all the way out to the end of the photographic plate.

195
00:31:41,000 --> 00:31:48,000
So if you have a diagramic molecule, all the rings in their intensity would look like a sine wave.

196
00:31:48,000 --> 00:31:59,000
Just from the beginning, up, down, up, down, up, down, the spacing would be identical between them aside from some geometric factors that I don't have to go into.

197
00:31:59,000 --> 00:32:16,000
All you have to do is to measure the frequency, oh, I should say that the farther apart the two atoms are that are giving rise to this sine wave, the greater the frequency of the sine wave.

198
00:32:16,000 --> 00:32:32,000
The two atoms that are far apart like this give a sine wave that goes up and down very rapidly, two atoms that are very close together will give a sine wave that has a very long wavelength.

199
00:32:32,000 --> 00:32:35,000
So you'll see very few rings.

200
00:32:35,000 --> 00:32:44,000
So all you'd have to do is to measure the spacing between these rings and that is related by theory to how far apart the atoms are.

201
00:32:44,000 --> 00:32:50,000
Well that's for a diatomic, let's say that's the case for a diatomic molecule. You only have one sine wave.

202
00:32:50,000 --> 00:33:02,000
The diatomic molecule vibrates and so the atoms are not rigid, they're moving back and forth away from one another like two balls on a spring.

203
00:33:02,000 --> 00:33:18,000
And of course that means that the distance isn't constant. Well it turns out according to theory to a good approximation, this sine wave instead of having constant amplitude all the way up dies off due to this vibration.

204
00:33:18,000 --> 00:33:27,000
So you measure the dying off of the sine wave and that tells you how big the amplitude of this vibration is.

205
00:33:27,000 --> 00:33:41,000
So we learn about two things, the distances between the atoms on the average and we learn about how much they're moving with respect to one another by measuring the damping off of the sine wave.

206
00:33:41,000 --> 00:33:56,000
Well of course there aren't many diatomic molecules left to study but every that problem or rather the theory that I mentioned applies to just the pairs of atoms.

207
00:33:56,000 --> 00:34:07,000
So if you have a molecule that has more than just two atoms in it you're going to have more than two distances, more than one distance.

208
00:34:07,000 --> 00:34:26,000
Every pair of atoms in the molecule gives rise to one of these sine waves. So carbon dioxide as a linear molecule is a carbon oxygen bond and that gives rise to a single sine wave that goes out.

209
00:34:26,000 --> 00:34:33,000
There are two of them but they have exactly the same distance so there are two sine waves that are right on top of one another.

210
00:34:33,000 --> 00:34:51,000
Then you have the distance between the oxygen atoms and that's twice as big. So it generates a sine wave also which has a frequency twice as great to first approximation as the frequency of the carbon oxygen because the distance is twice as long.

211
00:34:51,000 --> 00:34:58,000
And that gives a sine wave that oscillates with twice the frequency and the first one and they're on top of one another.

212
00:34:58,000 --> 00:35:13,000
So the pattern is no longer a simple sine wave but a collection of two sine waves. If you know how to separate out these sine waves and measure their frequencies then you know exactly what the structure of this molecule is.

213
00:35:14,000 --> 00:35:36,000
So CO2 were bent like NO2 is, NO2 would be entirely similar but there you would find the distances between the oxygen atoms, the distance between the oxygen atoms is not twice the distance between the nitrogen and oxygen because it's a triangular molecule like this.

214
00:35:37,000 --> 00:35:46,000
So oxygen-oxygen distance would not be moving twice the frequency of the NO but less than that.

215
00:35:46,000 --> 00:35:57,000
So you can immediately determine that distance and determine the nitrogen-oxygen distance and by comparing them you know what the bond angle is in the molecule.

216
00:35:57,000 --> 00:36:15,000
This simple account can be applied to molecules that are very, very complicated. The entire problem man is just to separate out what these different sine waves are, construct yourself a model that will account for all of the distances and then you have the structure of the molecule.

