01:23:58,000 --> 01:24:16,000
But the final folders are. There are several stages in the analysis of a structure. And they begin with the raw data that we get from using this microdensity

468
01:24:16,000 --> 01:24:28,000
data, which is the data that we get from the raw data. And these raw data are the first things that go into the folder.

469
01:24:28,000 --> 01:24:43,000
Now, a lot of things have to be done to that raw data because after all, you're taking what is a continuous curve and you're sampling it at very small intervals along it.

470
01:24:43,000 --> 01:24:58,000
And we have points that correspond to this. Now, when the plate or film moves across the dense automator, it goes across the middle and back out on the other side.

471
01:24:58,000 --> 01:25:10,000
So we scan the film from one side to the other. But all the time it's rotating, which means that half of the film should be identical to the other.

472
01:25:10,000 --> 01:25:18,000
And half of the trace should be identical to the other half. But since you're sampling by points, you can't make sure that these points are identical.

473
01:25:18,000 --> 01:25:30,000
So you have to do something as we call, find the center. So we have a program that compares the two sides of this and determines where the center is.

474
01:25:30,000 --> 01:25:40,000
And then it takes the data on one side and that on the other, interpolates if necessary between the points, adds them all together to give you a scan.

475
01:25:40,000 --> 01:25:50,000
That's all in there, finding the center. So we have the curve and counts. We have the curve curves that find the center.

476
01:25:50,000 --> 01:25:59,000
And then we have the data, which are just numbers. We want to convert them to something which has a common basis.

477
01:25:59,000 --> 01:26:11,000
And because of the properties of the dense automator, a very black film can give you the same range of numbers that a very light film can.

478
01:26:11,000 --> 01:26:26,000
But there's obviously a lot more scattering and one than in the other. So we have a way of converting this information to let us call it absolute densities.

479
01:26:26,000 --> 01:26:37,000
It's not really that, but it really puts the two curves on the same scale in terms of darkness and so on.

480
01:26:37,000 --> 01:26:53,000
Then we have a number of programs that are designed to convert this. There is a difference between the blackness of the film and the intensity of the scattering.

481
01:26:53,000 --> 01:27:07,000
Now, you can get a sense of this where, for example, if you take a film and expose it for a second, you get a certain darkness.

482
01:27:07,000 --> 01:27:24,000
Suppose that for two seconds, you get another darkness. And of course, if in the right range, the blackness of the second would be, if you expose twice as long under identical condition, the blackness would be twice as great.

483
01:27:24,000 --> 01:27:35,000
Well, clearly, the longer you expose, the less the photographic film is going to respond. So pretty soon it gets black and it doesn't matter how long you expose, not going to get any blacker.

484
01:27:35,000 --> 01:27:50,000
So the curve that relates blackness to intensity is not linear. We have to find out how non-linear it is in terms of how dark the film is.

485
01:27:50,000 --> 01:28:16,000
So we have corrections for that. We have a whole host of corrections that are built into this that is designed to take the data from the film and put it into a form which compares with mathematically with a theoretical function that we can calculate.

486
01:28:16,000 --> 01:28:25,000
And there are many steps in this process. Each one of these steps builds up to this point.

487
01:28:25,000 --> 01:28:39,000
And then, when we've got all of that, we then have, we do a number of calculations.

488
01:28:39,000 --> 01:28:56,000
The most important of which is the final fitting procedure. And it's called a least squares adjustment. And so this is a program that fits the final model to the experimental data.

